

D1. How?
This appendix outlines a practical, scalable infrastructure model grounded in Flow‑Core principles. It replaces heavy reliance on centralized electrical grids with decentralized, gravity‑based hydraulic systems using water as the primary energy carrier. The design emphasizes simplicity, visibility, repairability by residents, and alignment with natural tendencies (UP//DOWN gravitational storage). It is presented as a viable pilot concept suitable for engineering review and testing in Alberta conditions. This model supports ministries responsible for Energy, Municipal Affairs, Indigenous Relations, Environment and Protected Areas, and Infrastructure.

D2. Core Concept: UP//DOWN Gravitational Storage (上//下) 
Water is lifted to elevated reservoirs using solar thermal, wind, and human/play‑powered input. It is then released in controlled flows to drive mechanical systems through waterwheels and micro‑turbines. This creates a closed‑loop hydraulic metabolism that is:
Low‑maintenance and repairable with local skills and materials
Thermally stable through earth‑sheltering and thermal mass
Pedagogically legible — children can understand and participate in the energy system
Resilient in cold climates

The flow through the village is expressed as: 

米(上//下)

米 is the motion that turns the loom, spins the ventilation fans, and drives the salad‑room machines. It is not the sum of gathering and release. It is the expression of their relation. 上 is gathered potential: water stored at height, attention paid. 下 is released tendency: water descending, flywheel turning, fabric woven, words echoing forward into the next moment. The double slash marks them as inseparable complements — two conditions that cannot be pulled apart without ending the flow. Gathering without release produces accumulation, not energy. Release without gathering produces depletion, not energy. Only the slash — the living relation between the two — produces 米.
