D3. Proposed Pilot Scale (12‑Home Cluster)
Dome‑World is a gravity‑powered, closed‑loop village where water replaces electricity as the primary energy carrier, thermal stability is achieved through earth sheltering and passive solar design, and domestic systems are integrated into a single hydraulic metabolism.
Site Hydrology and Gravity Storage
The village sits between two concentric hills. The inner hill holds a reservoir at its peak where solar radiation warms the water. This reservoir is the system's primary potential energy store. At 10 metres of elevation, each kilogram of water stores approximately 98 joules of gravitational potential energy. Water descends through gravity‑fed channels regulated by simple manual dampers — valves that restrict or permit flow without requiring external power. Before distribution, water passes through black carbon bamboo filters produced on‑site through controlled pyrolysis.

Water Return and Closed‑Loop Logic
Water can be returned to the elevated reservoir through several complementary mechanisms including solar pumps and/or an Archimedes screw activated by a waterwheel‑turbine powered by the water's own descent, which lifts a portion of the outflow back toward the reservoir using gravitational energy released on the way down to partially offset the energy cost of return. This is not perpetual motion: there are net losses, and supplementary lifting is provided by wind‑powered pumps, small solar pumps, and play‑powered machines — pedal cranks, toy car mechanisms, and hand cranks safe enough for a two‑year‑old to operate independently. Redundancy is a design feature chosen deliberately in contrast to the six-sigma design philosophy that led to catastrophic supply chain shortages during the covid-19 pandemic. Flow-core systems are designed to absorb shock. On high‑energy days when rainfall or snowmelt produces surplus flow, overflow is directed through a series of decorative fountains and waterpark features, converting excess potential into pure joy rather than waste.

Hydraulic Energy Conversion
Descending water drives micro‑turbines and waterwheels that convert gravitational potential energy into mechanical work without electrical conversion. Micro‑turbines at points of steep descent drive flywheels, looms, and ventilation fans directly. Waterwheels in gentler channel sections provide continuous low‑speed rotational energy for the binary loom, wind closet bellows, and the salad-room machines (see D5 for a full catalogue of the salad-room machines)

Thermal Regulation
Cob houses built into the outer hillside achieve thermal stability through earth sheltering and thermal mass. The surrounding earth maintains approximately 10–15°C year‑round below the frost line. A solar chimney provides passive ventilation and air filtration. The translucent bamboo dome creates a microclimate 5–10°C warmer than external ambient temperatures in winter and the solar chimney and vine net regulate heat and humidity in summer. A shallow waterbed floor heated by solar‑warmed reservoir water provides radiant warmth to sleeping areas.

