D6. Key Components
Hill‑Supported Water Batteries: Individual hillside reservoirs (~59 m² at 1.5 m depth) for daily storage, with gentle overflow channels cascading between homes — a visible, audible "lazy river" that provides transportation, mechanical motion, as well as amusement.
The Bedroom: Each house contains a room dug halfway into the hillside whose floor is a heated membrane-covered shallow pool drawn from the elevated warm pool. Thin mattresses of latex, wool, feathers, and/or cotton rest on the waterbed surface and can be carried to the sanitation corridor for cleaning on an as-needed-basis, so there is no need for sheets. Three of the bed-room walls are packed earth lined with woven basket-like panels, wool pressed into them with pine sap and beeswax, and a cotton quilt hung over that so everything in the bed-room is soft, warm and dry. The fourth wall can be made of any material the dome-dweller likes, as it is sheltered by the dome and non-structural. Train car bunkbeds are built into the earth walls for small humans — secure enclosed sleeping nooks with translucent sliding doors that trap warmth and provide privacy. Bedding and walls are richly decorated with embroidery, handprints, geometric patterns, and the ongoing creative life of the family. The pillows are also the stuffies, so there is never anything to tidy away. They just live on the bed. The human dome-dwellers love to jump on the waterbed during the day, which helps with the water flow. Bars on the ceiling can be pulled down to turn a fan, which is really fun. 
Cōl‑Box & Hõt‑Box Thermal System: A visible, repairable cooling and heating loop using a belt‑driven compressor. The cōl‑box gathers cold for food preservation. Inside the wool insulated box, condensation runs down the stainless steel drinking-basin to form icicles which are chipped off and enjoyed in drinks and desserts. Dome-dwellers love to place fruit slices  on the stainless steel drip tray which they smash on the table to make frozen treats. Then they place the drip tray back on the slate slab and close the sliding wool-shoji-screen-door. Dome-dwellers hold cups under the overflow-spout of the cōl‑Box which pours into the terracotta salad-sink where we wash salad picked from the walls of the salad-room. The water then flows into the steam chamber of the hõt‑box where the compressor directs the flow of  hõt toward the toast drawer and grain-popping-barrel before it is absorbed by the boiling chamber and discharged upward as steam rises into the sanitation chamber.
Sanitation Corridor & Bathing Cascade: Dishes, clothing racks, and mattresses attached to a flywheel-charging-cable to assist them down a waterfall wash which descends from the salad-sink, through the steam-chamber, and terminates in the wind-closet. The warm water cascades through a thermal gradient of tubs, ending at the release valve which cleans the user when they perform 出.
Counterweight Ziplines: Safe, low‑energy transport using rider weight for balance. Your descent assists my ascent. The notation is carved into the platform posts: 下//上.
The-Window-Which-Cooks: A basket-like appendage that descends from the dome, woven with aluminum foil, which brings sunlight down below the vine net to a double paneled window which gets hot enough to bake in on sunny days. In the absence of sunshine, a candle or charcoal brick can be lit in the window-which-cooks to provide heat and light.
Binary Loom: A community Jacquard‑style mechanical loom powered by falling water. The loom weaves patterns that record seasonal and community data directly into fabric worn by residents. The woven cloth is cut and sewn into everyday clothing — tunics, wraps, blankets, and repair patches, as well as the mattresses and quilted walls of the bed-room. The village wears its memory. When the fabric wears thin, it serves its final purpose drying the human body after the release valve user performs 出, then returns to the soil through the fish pond or worm compost. This is a complete à//出 — no hidden servers, no abstract databases, only water, wood, thread, and human hands.

D7. Cōl-box Mechanics  
The cōl-box is not a hidden machine. It is an open alcove built into the thick cob wall of a dome home, designed so that anyone — child, elder, visitor — can see, hear, smell, and touch how cold is made. The ambiance of the nook itself teaches.
Here is how the tendency for cold settles:
1.  The drive
   A wooden pedal cart (or the gentle turning of the valley’s lazy-river waterwheel) spins a wide leather belt. The belt runs into the alcove and turns a simple mechanical compressor. No invisible electricity — just visible human (or flowing water) effort. When someone pedals, you hear the rhythmic clank and feel the shared work in the ambiance.

2. The compressor and ammonia
   The compressor squeezes ammonia vapor (R-717). As it is compressed, the vapor grows hot and wants to condense. This hot ammonia flows through pipes into the paired hõt-box next to it — where the tendency for warmth settles into useful heat: warm wash water, herb drying, or gentle underfloor warmth. Nothing is wasted.

3. The cold side
   After giving up its heat, the ammonia expands through a valve into iron pipes running beneath a thick slate shelf inside the cōl-box. As it expands, the tendency for cold settles strongly. The pipes and slate grow cold enough that moisture from the air condenses and freezes into visible icicles and frost. You can watch the crystals grow in real time. A shallow drip tray below catches the melt when the cycle pauses, keeping the nook clean and useful.

4. Safety and legibility
   Ammonia carries its own clear signal: a sharp, unmistakable smell if any small leak occurs. The system uses a low charge and stays in a well-ventilated cob alcove of the airy salad-room, so the ambiance itself warns and protects. No silent dangers.

5. Daily rhythm
 People pedal when ice is needed — for drinks, fruit-slice popsicles, preserving food, or celebration. The cold settles most strongly after steady pedaling. In deep winter the waterwheel may turn more slowly, so the box leans more on passive night cooling, but the ammonia loop still provides the clear, reliable cold when the community gathers. 
Everything is re-enterable. The same conditions — belt turning, compressor working, ammonia flowing — invite the tendency for cold to settle again and again, fresh each time. No hidden storage of “coldness.” Just the living loop made visible.
The infrastructure itself practices ambient cognition: the workings are not sealed away. The clank, the frost, the drip, the smell, the shared pedaling — all of it sits in the shared ambiance so that understanding arises naturally through relation with the place.
Children learn thermodynamics not by reading, but by pedaling and watching icicles grow. Elders rest their hands on the cold slate and feel the cycle. Visitors stand at the stoop beside the cat and suddenly understand how the valley keeps things fresh.
The ambiance around the cōl-box is one of honest effort, visible transformation, and generous return — heat to the hõt-box, cold to the shelf, knowledge to everyone present.

D8. hõt-box Mechanics 
Where the cōl-box invites the tendency for cold to settle, the hõt-box invites the tendency for warmth. They are not separate machines but two halves of one living loop, built side-by-side into the thick cob wall. One gives cold you can see growing as frost and icicles. The other gives warmth you can feel in your hands and use in daily life. Nothing is wasted. The ambiance of the nook holds both tendencies gently, teaching balance. 

1. The hot arrival
   After the compressor squeezes the ammonia vapor (making it hot in the process), the hot ammonia flows first into a set of iron pipes coiled inside the hot-box before continuing on its way to release its cold on the other side. This is where the captured heat settles.

2. The heat exchangers
   - A copper coil or thick stone mass inside the hot-box absorbs the heat from the ammonia.  
   - This warmth is absorbed into a boiling chamber which provides steam for the sanitation corridor.
   - Drying racks above the box where herbs, mushrooms, fruit slices, or damp clothes release their moisture in the gentle heat.  
   - In colder months, pipes may carry the warmth under nearby cob floors or into a small radiant bench where people can sit and warm their backs.

3. The rhythm and control
 The hõt-box grows warmest while someone is actively pedaling the cart or the waterwheel is turning. You can feel the difference with your hand on the warm stone facing. There is no thermostat or hidden control — just simple wooden dampers or valves that let people adjust how much heat stays in the box versus continuing through the system. When pedaling stops, the warmth lingers for a good while in the thermal mass, like a stone that has sat in sunlight.

4. Legibility and safety
   The hõt-box is just as open and visible as its cold companion. You can see the pipes, touch the warm stone, smell the drying herbs. Ammonia never mixes with the water or air — it stays sealed in its own loop. The gentle radiant heat and the faint scent of drying lavender or mint become part of the daily ambiance of the home.
A child finishes pedaling for ice and then runs to the hot-box to warm cold hands.  
Elders hang fresh mint and lemon balm to dry while sharing stories.  
Someone fills a basin with warm water from the tap on the side of the box to wash vegetables or a tired face.  
The paired boxes teach together: every act of making cold also makes warmth. The valley does not throw energy away. It lets one tendency (heat from compression) settle into useful forms while the other (cold from expansion) settles into frost. The whole system breathes as one.
In the shared ambiance of the alcove — the clank of the belt, the frost on one side, the soft radiant warmth on the other, the cat curled nearby — people naturally understand reciprocity and elegant cycles.

D9. Evaporative Cooling
In Domeworld we do not force cold with constant effort. We also invite the tendency for coolness to settle through the simple, ancient act of water turning into vapor. When water evaporates, it draws warmth from the surrounding air and surfaces, leaving a pleasant coolness behind. This method pairs beautifully with night sky cooling, passive solar rhythms, and the cōl-box, creating layered, living comfort shaped by the local ambiance.
How the tendency for coolness settles through evaporation
1. The wet cloth or mat curtains
   Simple, breathable fabric curtains or mats woven from local fibers hang in doorways, windows, or across air paths. A slow drip line from a small elevated tank (fed by gravity or the waterwheel) keeps them lightly moist. As warm air passes through or over them, water evaporates and the air cools noticeably. People can adjust the flow with a simple wooden valve. In the dry season, this brings a soft, moist coolness into the domes without any moving parts beyond the natural breeze or gentle convection.
2. The porous clay or cob elements
   Certain interior walls or alcoves use unglazed porous clay tiles or specially mixed cob that holds moisture. A thin film of water from the hõt-box condensate or a nearby cistern slowly seeps through. As it evaporates from the surface, the wall itself becomes a cooling radiator. Touch the wall on a warm afternoon and you feel the gentle coolness radiating outward. These elements are placed where air naturally flows toward living spaces.
3. The wind-catcher or solar chimney with evaporation
   Some domes have tall wind-catchers or solar chimneys used for ventilation. Inside the shaft, wet ceramic pots or dripping mats sit in the rising air path. Warm air drawn upward evaporates the water and cools before any remaining flow circulates back down into the rooms. At night this can combine with night sky cooling for deeper effect.
4. The courtyard or shaded garden loop
   Many domes open onto small central courtyards with a shallow fountain or misting channel fed by the water system. Water evaporates in the shaded space, cooling the air that then flows naturally into the living areas. The tendency for coolness settles strongest in the late afternoon when the day’s heat is highest and the air is driest.
Evaporative cooling works in harmony with the valley’s other systems  
- The hot-box provides a small amount of warm water that can be used for controlled dripping without wasting the heat cycle.  
- Night sky cooling pre-cools water or surfaces overnight, making daytime evaporation more effective.  
- The **cōl-box** handles the deeper, drier cold needed for food preservation, while evaporation provides comfortable room-scale cooling for people.  
- In humid periods the system is used lightly or not at all — the valley teaches reading the ambiance and responding accordingly.  
Evaporative cooling is deeply participatory and legible. You can see the damp curtains moving in the breeze, watch water slowly disappear from the clay, and feel the immediate drop in temperature. Children learn by helping fill the drip tanks or wetting the mats. The infrastructure itself shows the principle: water leaving as vapor carries warmth away, and the shared ambiance becomes cooler and more comfortable through this quiet exchange.
Nothing is hidden. The scent of damp earth and herbs often lingers in the cooled air, making the cooling itself part of the living sensory grammar of the valley..

D10. Materials and Maintainability
Primary materials include baumboo, cob, stone, terra cotta, wool, cast iron, stainless steel, aluminum, and concrete rubble. All major systems are designed for inspection, repair, and maintenance by residents without specialized credentials. Seasonal councils coordinate larger upkeep. Every system is visible; failure is legible; repair is non‑exclusive.
Independent verification of material safety — particularly for terra cotta, cast iron, and any salvaged metals — is essential. The work of Tamara Rubin (Lead Safe Mama) in conducting XRF testing on consumer and building materials provides a model for the kind of empirical, transparent screening that should accompany any pilot project.

D11. Governance and Relational Life
Community stewardship operates through rotating roles and seasonal councils. Maintenance is shared. No one household carries the full weight of the dome. As the saying goes in Dome‑World: *if your dome collapses, it's because you failed to maintain relations.”
Children's participation is carefully designed into the system: visible flows, safe play‑powered contributions, and the harvest of fruit from orchard trees with nets stretched beneath so small bodies can climb and reach without risk. Most of the labour of harvesting fruit is performed by children, who love to gather things to make their parents smile — a relational economy that eliminates the need for low‑paid farm labour, not by replacing workers with machines, but by restoring the harvest to its natural place in the life of the village.
In the salad room, salad grows on walls. The governing principle is known as Salad Law: if you see a neighbour making salad, you may walk by and ask if they will share — which they will, because abundance is the natural condition here, and sharing is not compelled by courts but by the sight of someone making food in full view of the meadow.

The same relational principles that govern the salad room — mutual witness, voluntary sharing, and the refusal of adversarial process — extend naturally to conflict resolution within the village. When disputes arise, they are addressed through facilitated dialogue and community accountability, drawing on the same Indigenous legal traditions that inform the parallel justice model outlined in Appendix F. Dome‑World has no courts of law in the Latin legal tradition. It has peacemaking circles, restorative conferences, and the understanding that a dome collapses when relations fail — not when rules are broken, but when the maintenance of mutual obligation is neglected. Professional resources that would elsewhere be directed into adversarial proceedings are redirected into facilitation, support, and the ongoing work of relational repair. 
An initial pilot is recommended at small scale (8–12 homes) to validate performance, safety, and cost before broader adoption. The regulatory pathway should focus on outcomes — safety, energy resilience, environmental impact — rather than prescriptive methods.

D12. Why This Matters
Dome‑World does not fight Alberta's climate or geography — it works with them. It reduces dependence on fragile centralized systems, lowers long‑term operational complexity, and creates infrastructure that teaches relational geometry and Flow‑Core principles through daily life. It offers a tangible alternative to the current trajectory of increasing energy demand and complexity.
The same infrastructure that provides resilience against Alberta winters — earth sheltering, charcoal filtration, closed-loop water and food systems, and passive thermal regulation — would, in the event of nuclear warfare and the prolonged atmospheric disruption that follows, offer meaningful protection against fallout, supply chain collapse, and the isolation of a world grown temporarily silent. 

D13. Relation to Flow‑Core Governance
UP//DOWN hydraulics, the cascading lazy river chain, the sanitation corridor, the bathing cascade, the cōl‑box, the hõt‑box, the kitchen heat recovery node, the counterweight ziplines, and the binary loom together operationalize the full Flow‑Core cycle. The loom is the most visible expression of ambient cognition within the village — memory not stored away from life, but woven into it, worn on the body, returned to the earth.
If enough Dome‑Worlds were built — enough sheltered atriums, enough hillside reservoirs, enough living vine nets breathing water into the air — the local weather itself would begin to change as new tendencies settle while we turn the winds to our favour.

D14. Legislative Statement
Infrastructural sovereignty is achieved by replacing centralized electrical grids with decentralized, gravity‑based hydraulic systems grounded in UP//DOWN (上 / 下) storage and tendency settling. Water is stored at height and released according to its natural tendency when invited by need. Return flow is powered by an Archimedes screw activated by the water's own descent, supplemented by wind and solar pumps and play‑powered machines safe for a two‑year‑old to operate — with surplus energy on high‑flow days directed through fountains and waterpark features rather than wasted. This same flow powers a living binary loom that encodes the village's memory directly into fabric worn as everyday clothing. The cōl‑box gathers coolness, the hõt‑box releases warmth, the kitchen heat recovery node cooks by recovered heat and river power, the sanitation corridor cleans by gravity, the bathing cascade warms by gradient, and the ziplines move people by counterweight — your descent assists my ascent. These are not amenities added to the infrastructure; they are the infrastructure. This model reduces dependency on external monopolies, strengthens community resilience, and aligns infrastructure with relational, ecological, and mnemonic flows rather than mechanical control.

D15. Time in Dome‑World
Time in Dome‑World is not Institutional Time. It is not the technology of certainty the Romans built — obligations with due dates, personhood anchored to a linear lifespan, moments specified and enforced. In Dome‑World, time is allowed to loop, braid, and remain ambiguous.
Time follows tendency, not schedule. The reservoir fills at the pace of weather. The cōl‑box gathers cold slowly, over hours. The vine net grows at the speed of photosynthesis. Dome-dwellers sleep when tired, eat when hungry, learn when curious. Deep engagement is protected. Rest is not a reward for compliance. It is a condition of life.
The four phases are daily experience. A dome-dweller wakes into fluctuation — the day unnamed. Walks into the salad room where icicles have grown overnight and ducks are quacking in the courtyard. Chooses — climb the mounds for berries, pedal the compressor for ice, jump on the trampolines. The morning takes shape. The cōl‑box holds the cold they helped make. The zipline carries them across the valley, and their descent helps a friend ascend. Then the morning releases. The light shifts. The icicles melt into the drip tray. The water returns to the spiral channels. They rest. The cycle begins again.
The seasons are the calendar. Spring gathers. Summer stabilizes. Autumn harvests. Winter releases. The infrastructure accepts dormancy. The fish pond freezes at its own pace. There is no deadline that overrides the season.
Time and memory. In Dome‑World, memory is tendency. The binary loom does not store a record of last season's rainfall. It weaves a pattern that carries the imprint of that rainfall into the fabric you wear. A small-dome-dweller who jumps on the trampoline today is not storing a memory. But the micro‑pulse they generated moved air through the wind closet. The air dried the dishes in the sanitation corridor. The dishes are clean because a child jumped. The dome-dweller may forget the jump. The clean dishes will not.
Time and death. Death is dissolution — the release phase of a cycle that has been present since the beginning. The wool on the shoji screen came from sheep who are no longer alive. The bunny fur came from rabbits who have returned to the meadow soil. Children help bury the dead rabbit. They spread the compost. They harvest the greens that grow from it. A human death is grieved openly, in the same salad room where the icicles grow and the water runs. The body may be wrapped in cloth from the binary loom — cloth that already carries the story of the village, now carrying one more story into the soil.
The riddle of time. Why am I structured this way? Because water settles and heat rises and children play and plants grow and the seasons turn regardless of what any institution declares. Because a life lived in cycles rather than deadlines is not less productive — it is more alive. Because the cat on the stoop already knew that time is not something you measure. It is something you inhabit.
